Here's a simple example of how MVP could be implemented in a login functionality:

Model:
```
public class User {
    private String username;
    private String password;

    public User(String username, String password) {
        this.username = username;
        this.password = password;
    }

    public boolean isValid() {
        return this.username.equals("admin") && this.password.equals("password123");
    }
}
```

View:
```
public interface LoginView {
    String getUsername();
    String getPassword();
    void showInvalidCredentialsError();
    void showSuccessMessage();
}
```

Presenter:
```
public class LoginPresenter {
    private LoginView view;

    public LoginPresenter(LoginView view) {
        this.view = view;
    }

    public void onLoginButtonClicked() {
        String username = view.getUsername();
        String password = view.getPassword();
        User user = new User(username, password);

        if (user.isValid()) {
            view.showSuccessMessage();
        } else {
            view.showInvalidCredentialsError();
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the Model is represented by the User class, which stores the username and password and checks whether the credentials are valid. The View is represented by the LoginView interface, which defines the methods to get the username and password from the user and to show error messages. The Presenter is represented by the LoginPresenter class, which acts as a mediator between the Model and the View. It handles the login functionality and updates the View based on the result. 

The View is implemented separately, and the Presenter is passed to the View as a parameter. The Presenter is responsible for handling the user actions (in this case, when the login button is clicked) and updating the View based on the result.

